 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · Logs of Numbers Less Than 1",
   "html": "<p>If $0<N<1$, then $\\log_{10}N$ is negative. We write it with a <b>bar characteristic</b>: e.g. $\\log 0.023 = \\bar{2}.3617$ meaning $-2 + 0.3617 = -1.6383$.</p><p>Method: shift the decimal so the number is in $[1,10)$; the number of shifts (negated) gives the characteristic.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "State the characteristic of $\\log 0.0025$.",
     "a": "$0.0025 = 2.5\\times 10^{-3}$, so characteristic $=\\bar{3}$ (i.e. $-3$)."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Calculations Using Log Tables",
   "html": "<p>Multiply, divide, raise to powers or take roots using $\\log(ab)=\\log a+\\log b$, $\\log(a/b)=\\log a-\\log b$, $\\log a^n = n\\log a$. Read antilog at the end.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Evaluate $\\sqrt{0.4356}$ using logs.",
     "a": "$\\log 0.4356 = \\bar{1}.6390 = -0.3610$. Half: $-0.1805 = \\bar{1}.8195$. Antilog $\\approx 0.6600$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Indices ↔ Logarithms",
   "html": "<p>The core identity: $b^x = N \\iff \\log_b N = x$. Logarithms are exponents written a different way.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Rewrite $\\log_5 125 = 3$ in index form.",
     "a": "$5^3 = 125$."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
